1. Introduction

rubric={points:3}

In this project we'll be exploring a dataset of New York City Airbnb listings from 2019. We will to start by downloading the dataset. Her we'll try to predict reviews_per_month, as a proxy for the popularity of the listing. Airbnb could use this sort of model to predict how popular future listings might be before they are posted, perhaps to help guide hosts create more appealing listings. In reality they might instead use something like vacancy rate or average rating as their target, but we do not have that available here.

Note there is an updated version of this dataset with more features available here. The features were are using in listings.csv.gz for the New York city datasets.

Spend some time understanding the problem and what each feature means. We can find this information in the documentation on. We can find an explaination of the features here.

The New York City Airbnb dataset contains different features related to Airbnb listing such as host_information, geographical information, listing attributes, price, review and availability. The dataset contains both numeric and categorical data types which may require different preprocessing techniques and there might me missing data which we need to deal with. We will build a predictive model to predict review per month which acts as a proxy for the popularity of the listing offering insights into how various factors influence the number of reviews a listing receives. It will involve data preprocessing, feature engineering, and regression modeling to achieve the predictive goal.

Initial observation

  • The numeric values have different scales so it will require scaling.
  • There is a class imbalance in neighborhood group and room_type class
  • The histogram of the price, minimum nights, number of reviews, reviews_per_month etc. shows most values are around the average value but it is right-skewed so there may be some listings with significantly higher prices, potentially indicating outliers.
  • The boxplots of 'neighbourhood_group' vs. 'reviews_per_month' and 'room_type' vs 'reviews_per_month' indicates variations in review frequencies across different neighborhood groups, with some groups having higher review rates than other and possible outliers.

Appropriate metrtics

Since we will be doing regression to predict 'reviews_per_month', the appropriate metrics for assessment should include regression metrics like:

  • Mean Square Error(MSE): MSE measures the average of the squared differences between predicted and actual values.
  • Root Mean Square Error(RMSE): RMSE is the square root of the average squared differences between predicted and actual values.
  • R-squared ($R^2$): This metric measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables. It provides an indication of how well the model fits the data.
  • Mean Absolute Percent Error (MAPE): This measures the percent of average absolute difference between predicted and actual values.ata.

5. Preprocessing and transformations

Data cleaning will be undertaken to ensure the dataset is ready for analysis. This includes identifying and handling missing values, correcting any inconsistencies in data formats, and removing duplicate entries if they exist. Next, different feature types will be identified, including numerical, categorical, and date features. Appropriate transformations will be applied to each feature type; for instance, numerical features may be standardized or normalized, while categorical features will be one-hot encoded to facilitate analysis. If necessary, a column transformer will be defined to streamline these transformations, ensuring that each feature type is processed correctly. Additionally, the number_of_reviews feature will be dropped, as it is highly informative for the target variable reviews_per_month, making it important to assess the model's performance without direct reliance on this feature.

7. Linear models

We will begin by applying a linear model as our first real attempt at modeling the data. To enhance the model's performance, we will carry out hyperparameter tuning to explore different values for the complexity hyperparameter. This process will involve utilizing techniques such as GridSearchCV to systematically evaluate a range of hyperparameter settings and identify the optimal values. We will report the cross-validation scores obtained during this tuning process, along with the standard deviation to assess the variability of the model's performance. Finally, we will summarize our results, highlighting the best-performing model configuration and any insights gained from the analysis, which will guide further steps in our modeling efforts.

For our first attempt we will use Ridge instead of vanilla linear regression as our linear model as this is a regression problem

In[31]:
#Lec-7 reference

scores_dict = {
    "alpha": 10.0 ** np.arange(-4, 6, 1),
    "mean_train_scores": list(),
    "mean_cv_scores": list(),
    "std_train_scores": list(),
    "std_cv_scores": list(),
}
for alpha in scores_dict["alpha"]:
    pipe_ridge = make_pipeline(ct, Ridge(alpha=alpha))
    scores = cross_validate(pipe_ridge, X_train, y_train_transformed, return_train_score=True)
    scores_dict["mean_train_scores"].append(scores["train_score"].mean())
    scores_dict["mean_cv_scores"].append(scores["test_score"].mean())
    scores_dict["std_train_scores"].append(scores["train_score"].std())
    scores_dict["std_cv_scores"].append(scores["test_score"].std())

results_df = pd.DataFrame(scores_dict)

The results of the linear model show that our model is not performing very well with any of the hyperparameters as the mean train and cv scores are really low. Our std scores are also very low. However, the results indicate that for Ridge regression, an alpha value of 10.0 provides the best mean cross-validation score. The model with this alpha value performs well in capturing the underlying patterns in the data while avoiding overfitting. As alpha increases, the model becomes more regularized, leading to a decrease in both training and cross-validation scores.



8. Different models

rubric={points:12}

We will try different models to see if any of them perform better than the linear model.

In[34]:
pipe_lr = make_pipeline(ct, Ridge(alpha=best_alpha))

    "decision tree": pipe_dt,

        'mean_score_time': (scores["score_time"].mean()),
        'mean_train_scores': (scores["train_score"].mean()),
        'mean_cv_scores': (scores["test_score"].mean())
    }

  • Decision Tree: It has a better train score than linear model but a pretty low infact negative cv score which means its not performing better than the linear model. The decision tree model shows signs of severe overfitting because of the large gap between training and validation score. While it achieves a perfect R-squared of 1.000 on the training data, it performs poorly on the cross-validation data (negative R-squared). The fit time is relatively high, indicating longer training time.
  • RandomForest: The random forest model has higher training and cv scores than linear model. But it exhibits overfitting, as the training score is higher than the cross-validation score. The fit time is significantly longer compared to the other models infact the highest of all models. However, it achieves a better R-squared on cross-validation data compared to the linear model.
  • LightGBM: The LightGBM model stands out as it achieves good predictive performance with reasonable fit and score times. It outperforms the linear model in terms of predictive accuracy, making it a potentially better choice.It achieves good scores for both training and cross-validation, indicating that the model captures the data complexity without significant overfitting.

10. Hyperparameter optimization

rubric={points:10}

We will try to optimize hyperparameters for the models we've tried and summarize the results. We can use sklearn's methods for hyperparameter optimization or fancier Bayesian optimization methods. Given are some examples of methods that can be used for hyperparameter optimization:

  • GridSearchCV
  • RandomizedSearchCV
  • scikit-optimize

We are going to use RandomizedSearchCV.

In[39]:
param_lr = {
    "ridge__alpha": 10.0 ** np.arange(-5, 4, 1),
}
param_dt = {
    "decisiontreeregressor__max_depth": np.arange(1, 20, 4),
}

param_rf = {
    "randomforestregressor__n_estimators": np.arange(1, 500, 100),
    "randomforestregressor__max_depth": np.arange(1, 20, 4),
}

param_lgbm = {
    "lgbmregressor__n_estimators": np.arange(1, 500, 100),
    "lgbmregressor__max_depth": np.arange(1, 20, 4),
    "lgbmregressor__learning_rate": [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
}

models = {
    "Linear Regression": (pipe_lr, param_lr),
    "Decision Tree": (pipe_dt, param_dt),
    "Random Forest": (pipe_rf, param_rf),
    "LightGBM": (pipe_lgbm, param_lgbm)
}

best_hyperparameters = {}
best_estimators = {}

for model_name, (model, param_grid) in models.items():
    random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(model, 
                                       param_distributions=param_grid, 
                                       n_iter=5, 
                                       n_jobs=-1)
    
    random_search.fit(X_train, y_train_transformed)
    
    best_hyperparameters[model_name] = random_search.best_params_

14. Takeaway

My most significant takeaway from the supervised machine learning material is the crucial interplay between data quality, feature engineering, and model selection. In practice, the quality of the dataset is paramount, as it directly influences a model's performance. So we understood the importance of data preprocessing. Besides effective feature engineering, the process of selecting, transforming, and creating features, can significantly enhance a model's ability to capture patterns in the data. Moreover, the trade-off between model complexity and interpretability is a vital consideration; the right balance ensures the model's generalization and usability. Besides hyperparameter optimization, interpreting evaluation metrics can be time consuming and subjective. Overall, I learnt the importance and how much time it need to do feature engineering, model selection, preprocessing and generalization.
